AB  - The Laristan mouflon is the smallest species of the genus Ovis with isolated populations spread mostly in the Laristan region in southern Iran. In recent years, this charismatic species has been considered as a conservation-oriented game species by the Department of Environment of Iran. Designating conservation planning of the Laristan mouflon necessitates identifying suitable habitats of the species and the habitat connectivity among protected areas of the region. In this study, habitat suitability of the species was investigated using species distribution modelling method based on the maximum entropy model. The map of habitat suitability was then used to assess habitat connectivity among protected areas based on least-cost path and circuit theory methods. The results showed that a mixture of undulating grass-shrub covers with proper availability of escaping terrains far from human-dominated areas characterizes suitable ranges for the species. The habitat connectivity analyses revealed that there is a strong connection among the existing protected areas, however, in some parts, due to the development of road networks, the bottleneck in habitat connectivity was observed. Results of this study could be considered as a practical tool for the conservation planning of this charismatic species in southern Iran.
