AB  - Testing the efficacy of downscaling in species distribution modelling: a comparison between MaxEnt and favourability function models.- Statistical downscaling is used to improve the knowledge of spatial distributions from broad-scale to fine-scale maps with higher potential for conservation planning. We assessed the effectiveness of downscaling in two commonly used species distribution models: Maximum Entropy (MaxEnt) and the favourability function (FF). We used atlas data (10 x 10 km) of the fire salamander, Salamandra salamandra, distribution in southern Spain to derive models at a 1 x 1 km resolution. Downscaled models were assessed using an independent dataset of the species' distribution at 1 x 1 km. The FF model showed better downscaling performance than MaxEnt, and the models that were based on linear combinations of environmental variables performed better than models allowing higher flexibility. The FF model minimized model overfitting compared to the MaxEnt.
